Facial Emotion Recognition using Deep Learning

Project Overview

  • Goal: Recognize facial expressions from images
  • Dataset: FER-2013 (Facial Expression Recognition)
  • Technique: CNN (Convolutional Neural Network) with Transfer Learning
  • Model: MobileNetV2 + Custom Classification Head
  • Output: Confusion Matrix & Emotion Predictions

7 Emotions Classes:

  1. Angry
  2. Disgust
  3. Fear
  4. Happy
  5. Sad
  6. Surprise
  7. Neutral

# ============================================
# DATA AUGMENTATION CONFIGURATION
# ============================================

#  FIX #2: Use the CORRECT preprocessing for MobileNetV2
#
# OLD (WRONG):
#   train_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(rescale=1./255, ...)
#    pixels become [0, 1]
#
# NEW (CORRECT):
#   preprocessing_function=preprocess_input
#    pixels become [-1, 1]  (what MobileNetV2 actually needs)


preprocess = tf.keras.applications.mobilenet_v2.preprocess_input  # 1
# Training data augmentation (to prevent overfitting)
train_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(
    preprocessing_function=preprocess,  # scales to [-1,1]      #2
    rotation_range=20,                 # Random rotation up to 20 degrees
    width_shift_range=0.2,             # Random horizontal shift
    height_shift_range=0.2,            # Random vertical shift
    shear_range=0.2,                   # Random shear transformation
    zoom_range=0.2,                    # Random zoom
    brightness_range=[0.8, 1.2],       # Random brightness adjustment
    horizontal_flip=True,              # Random horizontal flip
    fill_mode='nearest'                # Fill strategy for new pixels
)

# Validation and Test data (only normalization, no augmentation)
val_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(preprocessing_function=preprocess)
test_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(preprocessing_function=preprocess)

print(" Data augmentation configured!")

Step 4: Calculate Class Weights

FIX #2 Class Imbalance

English:

What was wrong: FER-2013 dataset is imbalanced. Some emotions have many more images than others:

  • Happy: ~9000 images
  • Disgust: ~500 images

So the model learns 'Happy' very well but ignores rare emotions like 'Disgust' and 'Fear'.

What we fixed: We calculate 'class weights'. Rare classes get a HIGHER weight. This tells the model: 'Pay more attention to rare emotions!'. We pass these weights to model.fit() using class_weight=.

:

: FER-2013 . :

  • Happy: ~9000
  • Disgust: ~500

'Happy' 'Disgust' 'Fear'.

: ' '. . : ' !'. model.fit() class_weight=.

# ============================================
# STEP 4: CALCULATE CLASS WEIGHTS
# ============================================

#  FIX #2: Compute class weights to handle imbalanced dataset
#
# OLD: No class weights  model ignores rare emotions
# NEW: Rare emotions get higher weight  model pays attention to all

classes = np.unique(train_generator.classes)

class_weights = compute_class_weight(
    class_weight='balanced',      # Automatically calculates the right weights
    classes=classes,
    y=train_generator.classes
)

class_weight_dict = dict(zip(classes, class_weights))

# Print the weights so you can see them
print(" Class Weights (Higher = model pays more attention):")
print("="*50)
for label, weight in zip(emotion_labels, class_weights):
    bar = "" * int(weight * 5)
    print(f"   {label:12s}: {weight:6.2f}  {bar}")
print("="*50)
print(" Higher weight = fewer images = model focuses more on it")

)

)

Step 5: Build the Model (Fine-Tuning)

FIX #3 Unfreeze Layers + FIX #4 Learning Rate + FIX #5 Label Smoothing

English:

FIX #3 What was wrong: In V1, we set base_model.trainable = False. This froze ALL layers. The model could only use features from ImageNet (animals, cars, objects). It never learned what emotions look like!

FIX #3 What we fixed: We freeze only the FIRST 100 layers (general features like edges, shapes). We UNFREEZE the LAST layers (they learn emotion-specific features). This is called 'fine-tuning'.

FIX #4 Learning Rate: Fine-tuning needs a SMALL learning rate (0.00005 instead of 0.0001). If the learning rate is too big, the pretrained weights get destroyed.

FIX #5 Label Smoothing: Some labels in FER-2013 are wrong (humans disagree on emotions). Label smoothing = 0.1 tells the model: 'Don't be 100% confident'. This makes the model more flexible and accurate.

:

FIX #3 : V1 base_model.trainable = False. . ImageNet ( ). !

FIX #3 : 100 ( ). ( ). 'fine-tuning' .

FIX #4 : (0.00005 0.0001). .

FIX #5 Label Smoothing: FER-2013 ( ). label smoothing = 0.1 : ' 100%'. .

In[28]:
# ============================================
# STEP 5: BUILD MODEL WITH FINE-TUNING
# ============================================

# ---------- BASE MODEL ----------
base_model = tf.keras.applications.MobileNetV2(
    input_shape=(IMG_SIZE[0], IMG_SIZE[1], 3),
    include_top=False,
    weights="imagenet"
)

#  FIX #3: Fine-tuning  Freeze first 100, unfreeze the rest
#
# OLD (WRONG):
#   base_model.trainable = False    ALL layers frozen
#    Model can NEVER learn emotions
#
# NEW (CORRECT):
#   Freeze first 100 layers   keeps general features (edges, shapes)
#   Unfreeze last layers      learns emotion-specific features

for layer in base_model.layers[:100]:
    layer.trainable = False       # Freeze: general features

for layer in base_model.layers[100:]:
    layer.trainable = True        # Unfreeze: will learn emotions

# Count frozen vs trainable
frozen    = sum(1 for layer in base_model.layers if not layer.trainable)
trainable = sum(1 for layer in base_model.layers if layer.trainable)
print(f" Frozen layers:    {frozen}")
print(f" Trainable layers: {trainable}")

# ---------- CLASSIFICATION HEAD ----------
x = base_model.output
x = GlobalAveragePooling2D()(x)

# First dense block
x = Dense(512, activation='relu')(x)
x = BatchNormalization()(x)
x = Dropout(0.5)(x)

# Second dense block
x = Dense(256, activation='relu')(x)
x = BatchNormalization()(x)
x = Dropout(0.4)(x)

# Output: 7 emotions with Softmax
output = Dense(NUM_CLASSES, activation='softmax')(x)

# Create model
model = Model(inputs=base_model.input, outputs=output)

# ---------- COMPILE ----------
#  FIX #4: Smaller learning rate for fine-tuning
#   OLD: Adam(learning_rate=0.0001)   too big, destroys pretrained weights
#   NEW: Adam(learning_rate=0.00005)  gentle updates
#
#  FIX #5: Label Smoothing
#   OLD: loss='categorical_crossentropy'               model becomes too confident
#   NEW: loss=CategoricalCrossentropy(label_smoothing=0.1)   more flexible

model.compile(
    optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=LEARNING_RATE),
    loss=CategoricalCrossentropy(label_smoothing=0.1),   #  FIX #5
    metrics=['accuracy']
)

print(f"\n Model built and compiled!")
print(f"   Learning rate: {LEARNING_RATE}")
print(f"   Loss: CategoricalCrossentropy (label_smoothing=0.1)")
model.summary()

Step 7: Setup Training Callbacks

What this does:

  • ModelCheckpoint: Saves best model based on validation loss
  • EarlyStopping: Stops training if no improvement for 10 epochs
  • ReduceLROnPlateau: Reduces learning rate when stuck
  • TensorBoard: Logs training metrics for visualization

:

  • ModelCheckpoint:
  • EarlyStopping: 10 epochs
  • ReduceLROnPlateau:
  • TensorBoard:
In[29]:
# ============================================
# STEP 6: SETUP CALLBACKS
# ============================================

# Save best model
checkpoint = ModelCheckpoint(
    BEST_MODEL_PATH,
    monitor='val_loss',
    save_best_only=True,
    mode='min',
    verbose=1
)

# Stop if no improvement for 10 epochs
early_stop = EarlyStopping(
    monitor='val_loss',
    patience=10,
    restore_best_weights=True,
    verbose=1
)

# Reduce learning rate if stuck
reduce_lr = ReduceLROnPlateau(
    monitor='val_loss',
    factor=0.5,
    patience=5,
    min_lr=1e-7,
    verbose=1
)

# Progress tracker  saves epoch info to JSON
class ProgressTracker(tf.keras.callbacks.Callback):
    def on_epoch_end(self, epoch, logs=None):
        progress = {
            'last_epoch': epoch + 1,
            'val_accuracy': float(logs.get('val_accuracy', 0)),
            'val_loss': float(logs.get('val_loss', 0)),
            'last_date': datetime.now().strftime('%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S')
        }
        with open(os.path.join(OUTPUT_DIR, 'progress_v2.json'), 'w') as f:
            json.dump(progress, f, indent=4)

callbacks = [
    checkpoint,
    early_stop,
    reduce_lr,
    ProgressTracker()
]

print(" Callbacks ready!")

 Callbacks ready!

print(" Starting V2 training...")

print(f"   Learning rate: {LEARNING_RATE}")
print(f"   Class weights: Enabled ")
print(f"   Label smoothing: 0.1 ")
print("="*60 + "\n")

start_time = datetime.now()

#  FIX #2: class_weight=class_weight_dict   fixes imbalance
#
# OLD:
#   history = model.fit(train_generator, epochs=50, ...)
#    All classes treated equally  rare classes ignored
#
# NEW:
#   history = model.fit(..., class_weight=class_weight_dict)
#    Rare classes get higher weight  model learns all emotions

history = model.fit(
    train_generator,
    epochs=EPOCHS,
    validation_data=val_generator,
    class_weight=class_weight_dict,    #  FIX #2: handle imbalance
    callbacks=callbacks,
    verbose=1
)

end_time = datetime.now()

print("\n" + "="*60)
print(" Training complete!")
print(f"  Duration: {end_time - start_time}")
print(f" Best model saved: {BEST_MODEL_PATH}")
print("="*60)

# PER-CLASS ACCURACY

def plot_per_class_accuracy(cm, labels):
    """
    Calculate and plot accuracy for each emotion class
    """
    per_class_acc = cm.diagonal() / cm.sum(axis=1)
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
    bars = plt.bar(labels, per_class_acc, color='skyblue', edgecolor='navy', linewidth=1.5)
    
    # Color bars based on accuracy
    for i, bar in enumerate(bars):
        if per_class_acc[i] >= 0.7:
            bar.set_color('green')
        elif per_class_acc[i] >= 0.5:
            bar.set_color('orange')
        else:
            bar.set_color('red')
    
    plt.xlabel('Emotion', fontsize=12, fontweight='bold')
    plt.ylabel('Accuracy', fontsize=12, fontweight='bold')
    plt.title('Per-Class Accuracy for Each Emotion', fontsize=14, fontweight='bold')
    plt.ylim([0, 1])
    plt.grid(axis='y', alpha=0.3)
    
    # Add value labels on bars
    for i, v in enumerate(per_class_acc):
        plt.text(i, v + 0.02, f'{v:.2%}', ha='center', fontweight='bold')
    
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.savefig(os.path.join(RESULTS_DIR, 'per_class_accuracy.png'), dpi=150, bbox_inches='tight')
    plt.show()
    
    # Print per-class accuracy
    print("\n Per-Class Accuracy:")
    print("="*40)
    for label, acc in zip(labels, per_class_acc):
        print(f"   {label:12s}: {acc:.4f} ({acc*100:.2f}%)")
    print("="*40)

# Plot per-class accuracy
plot_per_class_accuracy(cm, emotion_labels)

Step 15: Prediction Function for New Images

What this does:

  • Creates a function to predict emotion from any image
  • Displays the image with predicted emotion
  • Shows confidence scores for all emotions

:

In[14]:
# ============================================
# PREDICTION FUNCTION FOR NEW IMAGES
# ============================================

def predict_emotion(image_path, model, show_confidence=True):
    """
    Predict emotion from a single image
    
    Args:
        image_path: Path to the image file
        model: Trained Keras model
        show_confidence: Whether to show confidence scores
    
    Returns:
        predicted_emotion: The predicted emotion label
        confidence: Confidence score (0-1)
    """
    # Load and preprocess image
    img = tf.keras.preprocessing.image.load_img(
        image_path,
        target_size=IMG_SIZE
    )
    img_array = tf.keras.preprocessing.image.img_to_array(img)
    img_array = img_array / 255.0  # Normalize
    img_array = np.expand_dims(img_array, axis=0)  # Add batch dimension
    
    # Make prediction
    predictions = model.predict(img_array, verbose=0)
    predicted_class = np.argmax(predictions[0])
    confidence = predictions[0][predicted_class]
    predicted_emotion = emotion_labels[predicted_class]
    
    # Display results
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(12, 5))
    
    # Show image
    axes[0].imshow(img)
    axes[0].set_title(
        f"Predicted: {predicted_emotion}\nConfidence: {confidence:.2%}",
        fontsize=14,
        fontweight='bold'
    )
    axes[0].axis('off')
    
    # Show confidence scores
    if show_confidence:
        axes[1].barh(emotion_labels, predictions[0])
        axes[1].set_xlabel('Confidence', fontsize=12)
        axes[1].set_title('Confidence Scores for All Emotions', fontsize=12, fontweight='bold')
        axes[1].set_xlim([0, 1])
    else:
        axes[1].axis('off')
    
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
    
    # Print results
    print("\n Prediction Results:")
    print(f"   Image: {os.path.basename(image_path)}")
    print(f"   Predicted Emotion: {predicted_emotion}")
    print(f"   Confidence: {confidence:.2%}")
    
    if show_confidence:
        print("\n   All Confidence Scores:")
        for emotion, score in zip(emotion_labels, predictions[0]):
            print(f"      {emotion:12s}: {score:.4f} ({score*100:.2f}%)")
    
    return predicted_emotion, confidence

print(" Prediction function ready!")

 Prediction function ready!

# ============================================
# VISUALIZE PREDICTIONS ON MULTIPLE IMAGES
# ============================================

def visualize_predictions(generator, model, num_images=9):
    """
    Visualize predictions on multiple images from the test set
    """
    # Get a batch of images
    images, true_labels = next(generator)
    
    # Make predictions
    predictions = model.predict(images, verbose=0)
    predicted_classes = np.argmax(predictions, axis=1)
    true_classes = np.argmax(true_labels, axis=1)
    
    # Plot
    plt.figure(figsize=(15, 15))
    for i in range(min(num_images, len(images))):
        plt.subplot(3, 3, i + 1)
        plt.imshow(images[i])
        
        true_emotion = emotion_labels[true_classes[i]]
        pred_emotion = emotion_labels[predicted_classes[i]]
        confidence = predictions[i][predicted_classes[i]]
        
        # Color: green if correct, red if wrong
        color = 'green' if true_classes[i] == predicted_classes[i] else 'red'
        
        plt.title(
            f"True: {true_emotion}\nPred: {pred_emotion}\nConf: {confidence:.2%}",
            color=color,
            fontweight='bold'
        )
        plt.axis('off')
    
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.savefig(os.path.join(RESULTS_DIR, 'prediction_samples.png'), dpi=150, bbox_inches='tight')
    plt.show()

# Visualize predictions
print(" Visualizing predictions on test images...\n")
visualize_predictions(test_generator, best_model, num_images=9)
